<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-132-023 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 791 674</DOCID><JOURNAL>Business Week  June 10 1991 n3217 p78(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How much more can PC makers toss overboard? They've slashedworkers and prices - and haven't hit bottom. (Cover Story)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Buell, Barbara; Depke, Deidre; Levine, Jonathan; Forest, StephanieAnderson.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer companies frustrated over lack of growth and stagnantearnings have cut payrolls and slashed prices in anticipation ofan even tighter market.andP;  Companies, including Apple, which islaying off 10 percent of its employees, and DEC, which is expectedto cut 4,000 manufacturing jobs on top of the 9,000 positions itcut since 1989, will reduce their work forces even more.andP;  Even IBMplans to cut jobs: Since 1986, it has cut 47,000 workers throughearly retirement and other programs, but plans to cut 14,000 more.andO;An independent analyst says that IBM could cut an additional25,000 by 1993.andP;  IBM Chmn John F. Akers released a memo toemployees recently upbraiding them for their complacency at a timeof industry upheaval.andP;  Within the industry, price competition isreducing profit margins to a minimum.andP;  The most successfulcompanies seem to be well managed PC-clone manufacturers such asAST Research Inc and Dell Computer Corp. Their machines list for25 percent less than the top brands.andP;  The declining market may bebeneficial for consumers: prices may continue to fall asmanufacturers try to get out from under excess inventory.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Management).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Computer industryEconomics of ComputingFinancial StabilityReorganizationCompetitionOrganization Structure.andO;Feature:   illustrationportraitgraph.andO;Caption:   John Akers. (portrait)Shrinking payrolls. (graph)Person:    Akers, John (Records and correspondence).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>